/*
Memory Leak
Memory is allocated but never released, even when it’s no longer needed

Why Memory Leaks Are Dangerous

❌ Increased RAM usage
❌ Slower performance
❌ App crashes
❌ Browser tab freeze

Common Causes of Memory Leaks
1. Global Variables
name = "Aman"; // ❌ no let/var/const

👉 Stays forever in memory

2. Closures Holding Memory
function outer() {
  let bigData = new Array(1000000).fill("data");

  return function () {
    console.log("Hello");
  };
}

const fn = outer();

👉 bigData stays in memory due to closure

3. Unremoved Event Listeners
button.addEventListener("click", () => {
  console.log("Clicked");
});

👉 If button is removed but listener isn’t:

❌ Memory leak
4. Timers (setInterval)
setInterval(() => {
  console.log("Running");
}, 1000);

👉 Runs forever unless cleared

5. DOM References
let div = document.getElementById("box");

👉 If removed from DOM but referenced:

❌ Memory leak
6. Detached DOM Nodes (🔥 Important)

👉 DOM removed but JS still references it

7. Caches Not Cleared
let cache = {};
cache["data"] = largeObject;

👉 Keeps growing


How Garbage Collector Works (Simplified)

👉 Uses Mark and Sweep

Mark reachable objects
Remove unreachable ones

👉 Problem:
If something is still referenced → GC won’t remove it

*/
